Codebook for Replication study of Kerwer et al.(2020)

Here, were just setting a few options.

knitr::opts_chunk$set(
  warning = TRUE, # show warnings during codebook generation
  message = TRUE, # show messages during codebook generation
  error = TRUE, # do not interrupt codebook generation in case of errors,
                # usually better for debugging
  echo = TRUE  # show R code
)
ggplot2::theme_set(ggplot2::theme_bw())

Now, were preparing our data for the codebook.

library(tidyverse)
library(codebook)
codebook_data <- codebook::bfi
# to import an SPSS file from the same folder uncomment and edit the line below
# codebook_data <- rio::import("mydata.sav")
# for Stata
# codebook_data <- rio::import("mydata.dta")
# for CSV

## locate the rawdata file
zip_path <- list.files(path = "..",pattern = "jatos_results.zip",include.dirs = TRUE,recursive = TRUE,full.names = TRUE)
## import rawdata from zip file
df <- read_csv(unz(zip_path, filename = "rawdata.csv"))

## import text id table; script did not log text_id
text <- read_csv("../4_OS_Result/text_id.csv")

## Extract the system variables
df_sys <- df %>% select(starts_with(c("identifier","jatos","browser_","count_","date_","experiment_","screen_","system_","Start ","Last ","Duration","Batch","Worker ","State","Message")))

## Reserve the analytical variables in rawdata df
df <- df %>% select(!names(df_sys)[-c(1,2)])

## Split basic data
df_Basic <- filter(df, Q_type == "Basic") 

## Exclude the variables full of "None"
df_Basic <- df_Basic[,which(colSums(df_Basic!="None",na.rm = TRUE) != 0)]

## Split Belief data
df_Belief <- filter(df, Q_type == "Belief")
## Exclude the variables full of "None"
df_Belief <- df_Belief[,which(colSums(df_Belief!="None",na.rm = TRUE) != 0)]


## Split self evaluation data
df_self_eval <- filter(df, Q_type == "self_eval")
## Exclude the variables full of "None"
df_self_eval <- df_self_eval[,which(colSums(df_self_eval!="None",na.rm = TRUE) != 0)]

## Split post reading Question data
df_Post <- dplyr::filter(df, Q_type == "Post_survey")
## Exclude the variables full of "None"
df_Post <- df_Post[,which(colSums(df_Post!="None",na.rm = TRUE) != 0)]

## Split knowledge data
df_knowledge <- filter(df, Q_type == "Knowledge")
## Exclude the variables full of "None"
df_knowledge <- left_join(select(df_knowledge[,which(colSums(df_knowledge!="None",na.rm = TRUE) != 0)], -c("NH","OSA","text_order")), ## Erase IV variables because they are meaningless in test loop
  select(df_Post, jatosStudyResultId, NH, OSA, Text_id, text_order) %>% distinct() %>% mutate(Text_id = as.character(Text_id)),## Extract IV variables from df_Post
by=c("jatosStudyResultId","Test_id"="Text_id")) ## Add IV vriables to df_knowledge by Test_id 
## Error in `select()`:
## ! Can't subset columns that don't exist.
## x Column `Text_id` doesn't exist.
## Split Exit
df_Exit <- filter(df, Q_type == "Exit")
## Exclude the variables full of "None"
df_Exit <- df_Exit[,which(colSums(df_Exit!="None",na.rm = TRUE) != 0)]

# omit the following lines, if your missing values are already properly labelled
#codebook_data <- detect_missing( df, #codebook_data,
#    only_labelled = TRUE, # only labelled values are autodetected as
                                   # missing
#    negative_values_are_missing = FALSE, # negative values are missing values
#    ninety_nine_problems = TRUE,   # 99/999 are missing values, if they
                                   # are more than 5 MAD from the median
#    )

# If you are not using formr, the codebook package needs to guess which items
# form a scale. The following line finds item aggregates with names like this:
# scale = scale_1 + scale_2R + scale_3R
# identifying these aggregates allows the codebook function to
# automatically compute reliabilities.
# However, it will not reverse items automatically.
#codebook_data <- detect_scales(df)

Manage the variable labels and scales

library(labelled)
